This is from the first page of Greenhill & Co.=E2=80=99s Form 10-K from Feb=
ruary:Greenhill is a unique global investment banking Firm. Greenhill=E2=80=
=99s singular focus on advisory services differentiates us from other inves=
tment banks, and enables us to offer best-in-class, conflict free service t=
o each of our clients. Many of our peers as well as the large integrated, o=
r =E2=80=9Cbulge bracket=E2=80=9D institutions engage in commercial lending=
, underwriting, research, sales and trading and other businesses and invest=
ment management, all of which can create conflicts with clients=E2=80=99 in=
terests.Advising clients is our only business. We do not engage in investin=
g, trading, lending, underwriting, research or investment management busine=
sses. Our clients=E2=80=99 interests are our sole priority.We provide unbia=
sed, conflict-free advice. We have no products or additional services to cr=
oss-sell and, thus, no inherent conflicts of interest. We also have no lend=
ing, prime brokerage or other relationships with activist investors.Oh, wel=
l, you know. If you are a senior mergers-and-acquisitions advisory banker a=
t a big bulge bracket bank, you will grumble =E2=80=9Cugh, we have all thes=
e conflicts, I have to cross-sell derivatives to my clients, life would be =
so much simpler if I ran a boutique that only offered pure unconflicted M&A=
 advice.=E2=80=9D (Or: =E2=80=9CUgh, my business is so simple and capital-l=
ight; I never lose the bank a billion dollars; why does my bonus depend on =
these risky reckless traders?=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0And if you are a senior M&A ba=
nker at a small pure boutique, you will grumble =E2=80=9Cugh, I keep losing=
 business to banks that offer financing, life would be so much nicer if I h=
ad a balance sheet.=E2=80=9D Greenhill is  getting a balance sheet:Mizuho F=
inancial Group Inc. is forging further into US investment banking through a=
 deal to buy Greenhill & Co. as it seeks to accelerate growth.The Japanese =
banking giant agreed to buy Greenhill for $15 a share in an all-cash transa=
ction, which values the firm at $550 million including debt, the firms said=
 Monday in a statement. The lender will retain Greenhill=E2=80=99s leaders,=
 including Chief Executive Officer Scott Bok, who will be chairman of merge=
rs, acquisitions and restructuring. =E2=80=A6Mizuho is betting the takeover=
 will complement its investment banking teams.=E2=80=9CWe only recently beg=
an hiring M&A bankers in the last few years,=E2=80=9D [Mizuho Securities US=
A CEO Jerry] Rizzieri said. =E2=80=9CMizuho offers a full complement of pro=
ducts ranging from debt, equity, capital markets, derivatives, fixed income=
 and equity sales and trading, securitization. The piece that=E2=80=99s bee=
n missing has been M&A,=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThere are only two =
ways to make money in business, bundling and unbundling.=E2=80=9D In invest=
ment banking, there is unbiased, conflict-free advice, and there is  a full=
 complement of products, and you just sort of go back and forth.
 =20
   =20
      SoftBank as bank
   =20
 =20
One model of monetary policy is:=09When interest rates are zero, someone at=
 SoftBank Group Corp. sits around saying =E2=80=9Chow can we make any money=
 on investing=E2=80=9D and doodling words on a legal pad, and when she has =
enough words she holds the pad up at arm=E2=80=99s length and picks the fir=
st three she sees, and they are =E2=80=9Crobot=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cpizza=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ctruck,=E2=80=9D and she goes to her bosses and says =
=E2=80=9Crobot pizza trucks?=E2=80=9D and they say =E2=80=9Csure, that soun=
ds crazy enough that it might get us a double-digit return,=E2=80=9D and   =
SoftBank invests in a robot pizza truck startup.=09When interest rates rapi=
dly rise to 5%, startups with real products and recurring cash flow can=E2=
=80=99t go public, need to borrow money and will pay 12% interest for it, a=
nd SoftBank is like =E2=80=9Csure that=E2=80=99s fine, 12% will do.=E2=80=
=9DWhen rates are zero, people invest in far-future long shots. When rates =
are high, people make loans to actual businesses.   Anyway:SoftBank Group C=
orp. is working on plans to become a lender in the $1.5 trillion world of p=
rivate credit.=C2=A0Senior investors at the Japanese firm have spoken to ma=
rket participants about directly lending to technology firms, and touted th=
e possibility of deploying as much as $1 billion via SoftBank Investment Ad=
visers, according to people with knowledge of the matter. ...Deep-pocketed =
investors are finding opportunities providing debt to tech firms, especiall=
y as large software companies stay private for longer. There=E2=80=99s also=
 a hole in the market left by Silicon Valley Bank, which had been a major p=
rovider of debt funding to startups before its collapse.=C2=A0SoftBank is t=
argeting low double-digit yields for the strategy, the people said, which i=
s roughly the same as what most direct lending funds expect to earn.=C2=A0I=
 remember when   SoftBank used to target =E2=80=9Ccuring human sadness,=E2=
=80=9D not low double-digit yields, but that is what monetary policy can do=
.
 =20
   =20
      CS AT1s
   =20
 =20
Really the best way to pay investment bankers might be with additional tier=
 1 capital securities. If you pay them in cash, then they have the cash,=C2=
=A0they take money off the table,=C2=A0their wealth does not depend on the =
future performance of the bank, and they don=E2=80=99t care if it goes=C2=
=A0bust. If you pay them in stock, they have continuing skin in the game, b=
ut maybe=C2=A0too much:=C2=A0Their stock will go up a lot if the bank does =
well, but it can=E2=80=99t go below zero if the bank fails, so they have in=
centives to take risks and reach for higher profits. But the way that AT1s =
work is that they pay a steady fixed amount if times are good, and they go =
to zero if the bank fails. If you pay bankers in AT1s and they take huge ri=
sks that pay off, then their AT1s won=E2=80=99t be worth any=C2=A0more; if =
they take huge risks that go poorly, then their AT1s will be worth zero. AT=
1s reward bankers for preserving the bank.=C2=A0It is a good alignment of i=
ncentives.On the other hand if the bank does fail then the bankers whose bo=
nuses were zeroed  will sue:Credit Suisse staff are making preparations to =
sue the Swiss financial regulator over $400mn of bonuses that were cancelle=
d following the bank=E2=80=99s rescue by UBS.Thousands of senior Credit Sui=
sse bankers have a portion of their bonuses linked to the group=E2=80=99s a=
dditional tier 1 bonds, securities that were wiped out in the takeover orch=
estrated by Swiss authorities in March.Law firms Quinn Emanuel and Pallas, =
which are already suing the Swiss regulator Finma on behalf of investors wh=
o owned the AT1 bonds, have received multiple requests from senior managers=
 at Credit Suisse to take legal action on their behalf too, according to se=
veral people familiar with the matter.Elsewhere in  people suing Swiss auth=
orities over the Credit Suisse Group AG AT1 wipeout:Credit Suisse directly =
disputed the Swiss financial regulator=E2=80=99s basis for writing down $17=
bn of its additional tier 1 bonds, in a private letter aimed at sparing sta=
ff bonuses that were tied to the debt. ...The aggrieved bondholders earlier=
 this month forced Finma to hand over a decree it had issued to Credit Suis=
se on March 19 =E2=80=94 the day the UBS merger was struck =E2=80=94 orderi=
ng the bank to write down the AT1 bonds.The decree made clear that the regu=
lator believed a =E2=80=9Cviability event=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 a term in the =
contract requiring a writedown =E2=80=94 had been triggered because governm=
ent-backed liquidity facilities had also bolstered the bank=E2=80=99s capit=
al.However, bondholders also compelled Finma to hand over a subsequent decr=
ee issued on March 22 that makes clear that Credit Suisse disagreed with th=
is interpretation of the contracts.The second decree refers to a letter Cre=
dit Suisse sent to Finma on March 20 arguing that the contractual condition=
s had not been met for a writedown, stating: =E2=80=9C[Credit Suisse Group]=
 further argues that no contractual =E2=80=98viability event=E2=80=99 occur=
red because the state support did not have a capitalising effect.=E2=80=9DT=
he rough intuition here is that the AT1s provided that, if Credit Suisse ne=
eded a bailout, the AT1s would get zeroed. Credit Suisse got a bailout, and=
 the AT1s were zeroed. But what the documents actually=C2=A0said=C2=A0was t=
hat if Credit Suisse needed=C2=A0capital=C2=A0support from the government, =
the AT1s would be zeroed, and there is an argument that the government only=
 provided=C2=A0liquidity=C2=A0support.=C2=A0Elsewhere in disputes over the =
AT1s, we have   talked a   few   times about the hedge funds who are rubbin=
g sticks together to see if they can=E2=80=99t get the AT1 writedown to tri=
gger a payout on credit default swaps on Credit Suisse. Those credit defaul=
t swaps do=C2=A0not=C2=A0reference the AT1s, but they reference=C2=A0other=
=C2=A0Credit Suisse bonds, and you can make arguments. =E2=80=9CThe AT1s ar=
e somehow pari passu with the other bonds, so a writedown of the AT1s trigg=
ers CDS on the other bonds,=E2=80=9D say. Or: =E2=80=9CThe writedown of the=
 AT1s is a bankruptcy event, which triggers CDS on everything.=E2=80=9D Etc=
. So far no luck;   Bloomberg reports:A panel overseeing the credit-default=
 swap market has ruled that the government-brokered takeover of Credit Suis=
se Group AG didn=E2=80=99t constitute a bankruptcy event in which an insura=
nce payout could be triggered.=C2=A0The Credit Derivatives Determinations C=
ommittee said the fire sale of Credit Suisse to UBS Group AG was not a bank=
ruptcy credit event, according to a notice on its website. The question to =
the panel had related to both senior and subordinated Credit Suisse Group s=
waps.=C2=A0Hedge funds had been buying up the default protection in recent =
weeks, with traders scrutinizing the contracts=E2=80=99 documentation for g=
rounds for a potential payout. It=E2=80=99s the second time in recent days =
that the committee has ruled against the prospect of a payout in response t=
o questions posed by market participants.The latest query to the CDDC focus=
ed on whether the crisis of confidence in Credit Suisse equated to a bankru=
ptcy scenario, as per the terms detailed in the credit default swaps rulebo=
ok written by the International Swaps and Derivatives Association. This is =
despite Credit Suisse not having entered insolvency proceedings anywhere in=
 the world.For most technical purposes, Credit Suisse was entirely solvent =
and in fact quite well capitalized before, during and after the time it was=
 forced to sell itself to UBS for a song. It just doesn=E2=80=99t feel that=
 way.
 =20
   =20
      Libor
   =20
 =20
A crucial job of a banking regulator is to make sure that the public trusts=
 the banking system. Almost all of the time, the best way to do this is to =
make sure that the banking system is trustworthy: You supervise the banks t=
o make sure that they keep track of the money and make good loans and have =
plenty of capital and liquidity and don=E2=80=99t do fraud. And=C2=A0when a=
 bank is=C2=A0not=C2=A0trustworthy, you punish it and make it fix its probl=
ems, and you do this in public=C2=A0so that everyone knows that you are on =
the ball.But banking is in some essential way   a confidence trick;=C2=A0ba=
nks are stable if people trust them and unstable if people don=E2=80=99t. A=
nd sometimes a bank will turn out to be so untrustworthy =E2=80=94=C2=A0or =
so many banks will turn out to be untrustworthy =E2=80=94=C2=A0that it migh=
t undermine=C2=A0confidence in the banking system as a whole. And that woul=
d be bad. And really your core job is to make the banking system=C2=A0trust=
ed. If the biggest bank in the country=C2=A0comes to you and says =E2=80=9C=
oh hey we just looked in our vault and all the money is gone, what should w=
e do,=E2=80=9D you will be tempted to reply =E2=80=9Cshhh don=E2=80=99t tel=
l anyone.=E2=80=9D It would be better if the money was there! But given tha=
t it isn=E2=80=99t, it might be better not to tell anyone.And, again, confi=
dence in banks is sort of self-fulfilling. So even if a bank has done nothi=
ng wrong, and it comes to you and says =E2=80=9Chey our depositors keep tak=
ing their money out and we are getting nervous,=E2=80=9D you might be tempt=
ed to reply =E2=80=9Coh um maybe don=E2=80=99t mention that in public.=E2=
=80=9D And if its chief executive officer goes on television and says =E2=
=80=9Cactually our deposits are just fine, everything is normal, we are not=
 seeing unusually elevated outflows,=E2=80=9D you will squirm, a lot, becau=
se she is lying and that's fraud and you don=E2=80=99t like fraud and you w=
ant the banks to be trustworthy and so on. But you might also think she mad=
e the right call. Don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0tell=C2=A0everyone that there=E2=80=99=
s a run on your bank! Then there will definitely be a run on your bank!In 2=
008 there was a huge crisis of confidence in global banks, and one way that=
 that manifested is that the interest rates that banks paid to borrow money=
 went way up. Lending money to banks suddenly became a lot riskier, and so =
people charged more to do it; also it became more differentiated, and peopl=
e charged more to lend to risky-looking banks than they did to lend to safe=
-looking banks. The interest rates that big banks paid to borrow were colle=
cted and reported, at the time, by the British Bankers=E2=80=99 Association=
, which used a trimmed average of these rates as Libor, the London interban=
k offered rate, the benchmark interest rate underpinning trillions of dolla=
rs of floating-rate loans and interest-rate derivatives. This number was cl=
osely watched, both because it was hugely economically important to all tho=
se loans and derivatives and also because it was a good index of trust in t=
he banks:  The spread between Libor (the bank borrowing rate) and the Treas=
ury bill rate (the risk-free rate) was a simple way to measure bank credit =
risk. In 2008, that spread went way up, because banks looked a lot riskier.=
But Libor was based on banks=E2=80=99 self-reporting: The BBA would call up=
 a bank and say =E2=80=9Cwhat would you pay to borrow today,=E2=80=9D and t=
he bank would say =E2=80=9C4%=E2=80=9D or whatever, and the BBA would write=
 that down without really checking very much. And so banks rather famously =
  made up the numbers: When the real number was 4%, they might say 3.99%, o=
r 4.01%.=C2=A0The main reason that they made up the numbers was to make mor=
e money on derivatives trades: If an interest-rate-derivatives trader at a =
bank had a big swap that was resetting one day, and if he would make more m=
oney on that swap if Libor was higher, he would call his bank=E2=80=99s Lib=
or submitter and say =E2=80=9Chey buddy nudge that Libor a little higher,=
=E2=80=9D and the submitter would report 4.01% instead of 4%. This was a go=
od trade for a while, and several people at several banks did it, and event=
ually they got in trouble and the banks paid big fines and some of the trad=
ers went to prison.=C2=A0But the other reason that banks made up the number=
s is that,=C2=A0in 2008, when confidence in banks was faltering, you did no=
t want to report a high number. If every other bank was borrowing at 4% (or=
 said they were) and you reported 4.5%, everyone would know that=C2=A0you w=
ere the next bank to fail, that you were losing access to funding and were =
heading into crisis. So you just said 4%. And if your derivatives trader ca=
lled up and said =E2=80=9Chey I have a swap fixing today and could use a hi=
gher fixing=E2=80=9D you would say =E2=80=9Cnot now buddy, we got a banking=
 crisis here!=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The first reason to manipulate Libor =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0derivatives manipulation =E2=80=94=C2=A0was very much a bottom-up app=
roach: Traders did it because they wanted to make more money and get bigger=
 bonuses; it was a little trick passed down by word of mouth on trading des=
ks. The second reason to manipulate Libor =E2=80=94=C2=A0shoring up confide=
nce in your bank, or in the banks generally =E2=80=94=C2=A0was, uh, well it=
 was allegedly more top-down. Banks were not doing this to make an extra bu=
ck on their derivatives trades; they were doing it to survive. There have l=
ong been claims that this sort of Libor manipulation was encouraged by bank=
s=E2=80=99 senior leaders, or even by their governments.The Times of London=
   reported yesterday:A co-ordinated drive by national central banks and go=
vernments pressed banks to manipulate the Libor and Euribor benchmark inter=
est rates at the height of the 2008 financial crisis, an expos=C3=A9 to be =
published next week alleges.This was at the same time as dozens of former t=
raders were criminally prosecuted for much less serious rate =E2=80=9Cmanip=
ulation=E2=80=9D, it is claimed.A new=C2=A0book, exclusively serialised in =
The Times, claims that investigating agencies, including the FBI in the Uni=
ted States and Britain=E2=80=99s financial regulator, were told in November=
 2010 of an international drive to get Libor and Euribor rates down, regard=
less of the real cost of borrowing cash.Jurors in nine criminal trials for =
far smaller-scale interest rate =E2=80=9Crigging=E2=80=9D in London and New=
 York between 2015 and 2019 were never shown this evidence of manipulation =
by governments and central banks, the book claims.David Davis, the former B=
rexit secretary, has called for an inquiry into claims that =E2=80=9CBritis=
h and US authorities covered up state involvement in Libor-rigging and the =
scapegoating of low and middle-ranking bankers, some of whom have spent yea=
rs in jail=E2=80=9D. The MP also expressed concerns in parliament that the =
Treasury select committee =E2=80=9Cmay have been misled by state agencies a=
bout the knowledge and involvement of the state in setting false rates=E2=
=80=9D. =E2=80=A6The evidence of alleged manipulation by central banks and =
governments is set out in=C2=A0Rigged, a forthcoming book by Andy Verity, t=
he BBC=E2=80=99s economics correspondent, which shows evidence of central b=
anks pressuring commercial banks into publishing rates that were artificial=
ly low to calm panic in financial markets.The investigation found evidence =
that in October 2008, the Bank of England and the European Central Bank, al=
ong with three European national central banks and the Federal Reserve Bank=
 of New York, intervened in the setting of Libor and Euribor. The UK govern=
ment also allegedly was involved in pressuring banks to =E2=80=9Cmanipulate=
=E2=80=9D Libor =E2=80=94 meaning, as defined by criminal courts, seeking t=
o obtain movements in the benchmark while =E2=80=9Cdisregarding the proper =
basis for setting Libor=E2=80=9D.=C2=A0I have no idea if this is true; peop=
le have been saying this stuff for 15 years without, so far, much in the wa=
y of a smoking gun, and the BoE and other regulators all   deny it. What I =
will say is:=09The manipulating-Libor-to-maintain-confidence stuff and the =
manipulating-Libor-to-cheat-on-derivatives stuff are conceptually distinct.=
 The derivatives traders were not =E2=80=9Cscapegoated=E2=80=9D for this al=
leged manipulation; they were doing entirely separate manipulation. You cou=
ld imagine saying =E2=80=9Cwell manipulating Libor at the request of your r=
egulator is just good banking, but manipulating Libor to make money on deri=
vatives trades is fraud.=E2=80=9D But nobody really=C2=A0did=C2=A0say that;=
 convicting the derivatives traders of fraud required the government to cla=
im that Libor was meant to be objective and true, and that the traders unde=
rmined this objectivity.=09I mean ... if the regulators and central banks=
=C2=A0did=C2=A0tell the banks to keep Libor low, that would be understandab=
le? That might be how you do bank regulation in a crisis. You just don=E2=
=80=99t talk about it afterward.
 =20
   =20
      Securitized horse
   =20
 =20
One=C2=A0important move in modern finance is that you have some asset with =
some expected cash flows, and you slice up the cash flows and sell them to =
investors as securities. This allows the assets to be financed, the risks t=
o be allocated, ownership to be shared, etc.One important move in postmoder=
n finance is something like =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s turn gambling into secur=
ities and securities into gambling.=E2=80=9D Like:=09Gambling is fun, but k=
ind of frowned upon.=09Financial markets are huge business, but kind of ser=
ious and daunting.If you can   take a stock and   turn it into a   fun gamb=
ling game, you=E2=80=99ve got something. If you can take a fun gambling gam=
e and turn it into serious   securities, you=E2=80=99ve got something.=C2=
=A0Dana O=E2=80=99Neil at the Athletic reports about some guys who are  sec=
uritizing racehorses:The concept is simple: Buy a share in a racehorse =E2=
=80=94 for as little as $50 =E2=80=94 and then, if all goes well, earn a cu=
t of its winnings. The effect on horse racing could be downright revolution=
ary. Forty-one tracks have closed since 2000; two years ago, Arlington, out=
side of Chicago, shuttered after more than 100 years in existence. Some of =
the remaining tracks have been saved and salvaged by casinos, existing in, =
at best, an uncomfortable relationship. Most casino owners don=E2=80=99t ne=
cessarily want to run racetracks. The sport is in desperate search of both =
new fans and relevance outside of its three Triple Crown Saturdays. Despite=
 all the folks who love a good Derby party, not many come back to the track=
.Commonwealth may not solve the riddle entirely, but it definitely can help=
.=C2=A0Since Mage=E2=80=99s Derby win, 8,000 people have signed up for the =
app. That=E2=80=99s 400 more than went back to Churchill last Thursday, on =
the first day of live racing after the Kentucky Derby. =E2=80=9CHonestly, i=
n my opinion, this is the biggest way possible to grow the sport,=E2=80=99=
=E2=80=99 says Preston Troutt, whose horse racing roots run deep via his fa=
mily=E2=80=99s storied WinStar Farms, and who has led the traditional farm =
into an unorthodox partnership with Commonwealth. =E2=80=9CYou don=E2=80=99=
t need to know a single thing about horse racing. You don=E2=80=99t have to=
 grow up in the industry. If you=E2=80=99re willing to put in $50 and risk =
losing it, you=E2=80=99re in with an experience that=E2=80=99s unlike any o=
ther out there.=E2=80=99=E2=80=99Yes right you can solve the decline of hor=
se racing by turning it into stock investing because stock investing is fun=
 now, and also somehow vice versa. It would be fun to run an activist campa=
ign, do a hostile takeover of a horse and change his training regimen or le=
t him retire.=C2=A0Anyway they won the Kentucky Derby, which is more than y=
ou can say for the 2,000 startups that are like =E2=80=9Csell shares of you=
r home equity=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbuy shares of rare bourbon=E2=80=9D or w=
hatever.
