<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">The deposit franchise</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic question about this year=E2=
=80=99s US regional banking crisis is =E2=80=9Cwhy weren=E2=80=99t the bank=
s prepared for the very predictable problems that they faced when interest =
rates went up,=E2=80=9D and the basic answer is =E2=80=9Cbecause they thoug=
ht rates going up would be=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for them.=E2=80=9D</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/31560440.284426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDA1MjIyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB97e9682e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked about this</a>=C2=A0a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31560440.284426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDkvaXQtcy1uZXZlci10b28=
tbGF0ZS1mb3ItYmFua3MtdG8taGVkZ2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyMjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX2=
1lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTIyJnV0bV9jY=
W1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75a0810e" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  few ti=
mes</a> around here, and I have=C2=A0described=C2=A0two theories of banking=
. In Theory 1, banks=C2=A0have short-term deposits and invest them in long-=
term assets, so when interest rates go up, their costs go up (they have to =
pay more on their deposits) while the value of their assets goes down (thos=
e assets continue to pay fixed rates, and now are worth less). Rising rates=
 are bad. In Theory 2, bank deposits are=C2=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>long-t=
erm, because the banks have enduring relationships with their customers and=
 their customers are unlikely to leave, or demand higher rates, as interest=
 rates go up. And so banks can use those long-term-ish deposits to fund lon=
g-term assets, and as interest rates go up, the banks can earn higher rates=
, don=E2=80=99t have to pay higher rates, and so make more money. Rising ra=
tes are good. Theory 2 is the traditional theory of banking, and it is why =
many banks were not adequately prepared for rising rates.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">At the Wall Street Journal today, Jonathan Weil and Peter Ru=
degeair <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31560440.2=
84426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9iYW5rLXJ1bnMtdHJhc2gtbG9uZy1oZ=
WxkLWFzc3VtcHRpb24tb24tZGVwb3NpdHMtNDc0YWZjYzU_bW9kPWxlYWRfZmVhdHVyZV9iZWxv=
d19hX3BvczE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB11dd51a1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> report on Theory 2<=
/a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The recent spate of bank f=
ailures is upending a long-held theory among banking executives and regulat=
ors=E2=80=94that the value of a lender=E2=80=99s deposit business goes up w=
hen interest rates move higher.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The theory =
rests on an assumption: That banks don=E2=80=99t have to pay depositors muc=
h to keep their money around, even as rates rise. The deposits would be a s=
table source of low-cost funding while the bank earned more money lending a=
t higher rates.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The more rates rose, the bi=
gger the franchise value of those deposits would become=E2=80=94a natural h=
edge against the declining market values of a portfolio of fixed-rate loans=
 and bonds.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if rising rates or plunging=
 asset values cause a bank=E2=80=99s depositors to flee en masse, the franc=
hise value is zero=E2=80=94and, worse, it could beget other bank runs. That=
 is what happened with Silicon Valley Bank. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The Federal Reserve, which both regulates banks and sets interes=
t-rate policy, in a November report pointed to large unrealized losses on b=
anks=E2=80=99 bondholdings due to rising rates. Things weren=E2=80=99t so b=
ad, the Fed said, because =E2=80=9Cthe value of banks=E2=80=99 deposit fran=
chise increases and provides a buffer against these unrealized losses.=E2=
=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not really! And yet The=
ory 2 has some truth to it, just <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31560440.284426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYmYzM2Uz=
MTEtYzA4OS00MmNlLWIyYjAtODVhNTQ3NWFkNTcx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9655cd73"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> not so much for regional banks</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase lifted its outlook for how much it expects to=
 earn this year from its lending business following the recent purchase of =
First Republic, bucking a broader trend among US banks of shrinking profits=
 owing to deposit withdrawals.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a present=
ation for its investor day on Monday, JPMorgan lifted its 2023 target for n=
et interest income (NII), excluding its trading division, to about $84bn fr=
om $81bn previously, because of its deal for First Republic. NII is the dif=
ference between what banks pay on deposits and what they earn from loans an=
d other assets. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Large lenders suc=
h as JPMorgan have benefited from the US Federal Reserve lifting interest r=
ates last year, which enabled them to charge borrowers more for loans witho=
ut passing on significantly higher rates to savers.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">The bank said its deposits, which totalled $2.3tn at the end of Ma=
rch, were =E2=80=9Cdown slightly=E2=80=9D year on year. Chief financial off=
icer Jeremy Barnum said the expectation was that system-wide deposits at US=
 banks would continue to decline as the Fed tightened monetary policy and c=
ustomers chased better yields on their cash.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">=E2=80=9CWe will fight to keep primary banking relationships but we are n=
ot going to chase every dollar of deposit balances,=E2=80=9D Barnum added.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan is paying 1.21 per cent on average=
 to depositors, lower than the 1.75 per cent average of its peers, accordin=
g to data from industry tracker BankReg.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">See, <em>that=E2=80=99s </em>a deposit franchise. Having a valua=
ble deposit franchise means that you don=E2=80=99t have to chase every doll=
ar of deposits, because they don=E2=80=99t go anywhere.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Elsewhere in banking theory, here is Alex Harris at Bloomberg =
Businessweek <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31560=
440.284426/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUt=
MTkvb25lLXdheS10by1wcmV2ZW50LWFuLXN2Yi1zdHlsZS1jb2xsYXBzZS1mZWQtYmFuay1hY2N=
vdW50cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTIyMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
